>The Hanseatic League meets for the last time in Lubeck
>A German Scientist isolates and discovers phosphorous
>The Violin is invented

India and the Islamic World
>The Mughals attempt to enforce the Jizya tax and destroy some hindu temples, beginning a large Hindu rebellion
>A famine in Bengal kills millions

East Asia and the Orient
>Shakushain's Rebellion begins in Japan, led by merchants and other of the social middle class to open up Japan to allow them to trade with the world
>The Qing Emperor of China ends the Great Clearance

History class is intended for kids, so it tends to be kept short and sweet. Even all the stuff you've learned about WWII is incomplete, and sometimes downright wrong. And everything you learn in school is influenced by politics, the most direct and neutral example of which being that you will learn mostly stuff that's relevant for your country in both time and place (though that's also under fire for obvious reasons). I'm from a strange background, so for me it was immediately obvious in school that the classes we got were incomplete.

The history rabbit hole never ends. Loads of shit happened, and nearly all pop history is wrong to one degree or another. We had a short while where even pop culture made a good attempt at portraying history as faithfully as possible, but I fear we're reached the end of that already. At least it was long enough for a lot of renewed interest to spring up, so now we've got shitloads of amateur historians with access to primary sources who have developed the skills to use them.

>rock salt wouldn't make for an effective load for a shotgun shell
Well, you're wrong. Rock salt will tear you open and embed chunks of salt in your flesh. It was commonly used as a non-lethal load for about two centuries. It's rare these days because the injuries can be pretty severe, especially if you get hit in the face and lose your eyes.

No, it does not dissolve into a "white cloud of salt." It travels at velocity, higher velocity than lead at short ranges (10 to 20 meters) where a shotgun is intended to be used. It's more like getting hit with a load of broken glass. It's a very nasty shotgun load, and the way it tears your flesh can leave severe disfiguring scars depending on how much, if any, clothing it has to penetrate before ripping you open.

> t. I hand load 12 & 20 gauge shotgun shells.

> t. I've blasted 8-10" holes through 1/2" plywood at 10-15 feet with them.

Old Hollywood movies and Three Stooges comedies are not firearm training materials. A rock salt load will fuck your day up and is no fucking joke.
